{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491073"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:31:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"823"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/823"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.04,0.84,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/823"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71434"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3510"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of increasing pain and discomfort in his feet. The pain occasionally radiates up his calves and significantly disrupts his sleep. Over-the-counter pain relievers have not provided relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hypertension and takes perindopril. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks four cans of beer daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His feet show no open sores, wounds, ulcers; no signs of fungal infection like discolouration, thickening or crumbling are noted. His feet feel warm to touch with palpable peripheral pulses of equal volume. Capillary refill is slightly delayed over the left hallux. Passive and active movement of his feet do not reproduce the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonofilament testing shows reduced sensation with 6/10 test points felt bilaterally. Light touch sensation is impaired bilaterally and only felt at the mid-calf. Vibration sense is impaired at the first hallux but intact at the ankles bilaterally. Knee reflexes are intact bilaterally, but ankle and plantar reflexes are diminished. Heel-to-shin test is normal. Upper limb examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERandom blood glucose is 11.7 mmol/L (3.9-7.8). Glycated haemoglobin is 8.5% (4.0-6.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcoholic neuropathy","Peripheral arterial disease","Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease","Diabetic neuropathy","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of peripheral neuropathy including sensory loss, pain and reduced reflexes in a symmetrical distribution. The elevated random glucose and glycated haemoglobin indicate previously undiagnosed diabetes mellitus. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a distal symmetrical pattern affecting the feet first, with reduced sensation to multiple modalities and diminished reflexes as seen here. It is a length-dependent axonal neuropathy that begins distally and progresses proximally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E presents with both sensory and motor symptoms in a non-length-dependent pattern. It typically affects both upper and lower limbs simultaneously and may be accompanied by autonomic features. Patients often have concurrent nutritional deficiencies, particularly thiamine, which can contribute to the neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral arterial disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes intermittent claudication (pain on exertion relieved by rest) and critical limb ischaemia (rest pain, ulceration). While neuropathic symptoms can occur, the hallmark findings are reduced pulses, cool extremities, and pallor. The preserved pulses and warm feet here make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECharcot-Marie-Tooth disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy characterised by distal muscle weakness and wasting, particularly in the peroneal muscles leading to foot drop. High arched feet (pes cavus) and hammer toes are common. The late age of onset and predominantly sensory symptoms are inconsistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy that typically develops over days to weeks. It presents with ascending weakness starting in the legs and progressing upwards, accompanied by areflexia. Sensory symptoms are usually mild compared to motor involvement, and autonomic dysfunction is common. The chronic progression and preserved upper limb reflexes make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral neuropathy commonly presents with distal sensory loss, pain and reduced reflexes in a symmetrical distribution","Diabetes mellitus should be considered in patients presenting with peripheral neuropathy even without a known diagnosis","Multiple risk factors including alcohol, smoking and diabetes can contribute to peripheral neuropathy"],"references":["Selvarajah D, Kar D, Khunti K, Davies MJ, Scott AR, Walker J, Tesfaye S. Diabetic peripheral neuropathy: advances in diagnosis and strategies for screening and early intervention. Lancet Diabetes Endocrinol. 2019 Dec;7(12):938-948. doi: 10.1016/S2213-8587(19)30081-6. Epub 2019 Oct 14. PMID: 31624024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71434"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"823"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71434"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:18:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:20:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"823"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General